<HEAD>Court Asks Administration Opinion on `Lemon Laws'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today asked the Bush
administration whether state ``lemon laws'' should be allowed to
give buyers of chronically defective automobiles more legal
protection than they receive under federal law.
   The court invited Justice Department lawyers to comment on
arguments by domestic and foreign car makers that such state laws
impermissibly conflict with federal law.
   The justices are not expected to say whether they will grant
review to the manufacturers' appeal until hearing from the
government, which could take months.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled against the car
makers when it upheld New York's lemon law last March.
   ``Congress did not intend to occupy the field of informal
dispute resolution mechanisms (and) it is possible to comply with
both the New York and federal schemes,'' the appeals court ruled in
giving car consumers a significant victory.
   Congress in 1975 passed the Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act, aimed at
giving consumers more information about the warranties provided on
the new cars they buy. The law does not require that a warranty be
provided, but requires that if one is given it not be misleading.
   The law also permits car manufacturers to require consumers with
complaints about the cars they bought to resort to some informal
type of dispute resolution, such as arbitration, before suing.
   The federal law was not successful in resolving consumer
problems with chronically defective cars, and many states responded
by assing their own lemon laws.
   The New York law, enacted in 1983, requires manufacturers to
give consumers full refunds or to replace defective cars if unable
to repair the same problem after four tries or if a car is out of
service for 30 days or more within the first two years or 18,000
miles of operation.
   The law was amended in 1986 to make any arbitration decision
binding on car manufacturers but not on consumers and to entitle
consumers to oral arbitration hearings.
   The Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association and the Association
of International Automobile Manufacturers sued over the 1986
amendments. A federal judge ruled that the amendments are
pre-empted by the Magnuson-Moss Act, but the 2nd Circuit court
reversed that ruling.
   The case is Motor Vehicles Manufacturers Association vs. Abrams,
89-2026.
</TEXT>
