<HL>
   Justices Don't Limit Punitive Damages;
   Bank's Challenge of Fed to Be Considered
   ---
   Court to Decide If Regulator
   Can Force Bank Firms
   To Bail Out Ailing Units
   ----
   By Stephen Wermiel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
03/05/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   M
</CO>
<IN>
CENTRAL U.S. BANKS (BAC)
BANKS (BNK)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Supreme Court will decide the legality
of a weapon the Federal Reserve Board says is critical in
regulating bank holding companies -- the power to force them
to bail out their ailing bank subsidiaries.
   The justices agreed to hear an appeal by the Fed
challenging the May 1990 ruling of a federal appeals court in
New Orleans in favor of MCorp, a Dallas bank holding company.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The dispute concerns the Fed's "source of strength"
doctrine, which requires bank holding companies to use their
own assets to help their bank units that are in "financial
stress or adversity." The doctrine was applied by the Fed on
a case-by-case basis until it was adopted in formal
regulations issued in 1984 and 1987. Just the threat of
administrative proceedings, however, has often been enough to
spur bank holding companies to assist their ailing banks.
   In 1989, the Fed told MCorp that it would begin
administrative action to require MCorp and its subsidiaries
to come to the rescue of ailing banks. MCorp responded by
challenging the Fed's authority in federal bankruptcy court.
At about the same time, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
in March 1989 declared 20 of MCorp's 25 bank units insolvent
and in federal receivership. The 20 banks were sold later to
Banc One Corp. of Columbus, Ohio.
   The Fed succeeded in moving MCorp's case from bankruptcy
court to federal district court. In June 1989, the district
court barred the Fed from continuing enforcement proceedings
against MCorp.
   In May 1990, the New Orleans appeals court agreed with the
district court that the Fed exceeded its authority in its
source of strength rules. While agreeing to hear the Fed's
appeal, the high court also agreed to hear an MCorp appeal
over a separate issue in the New Orleans court's ruling.
   The justices will decide whether a bankruptcy court,
supervising a bank holding company in Chapter 11
reorganization, may block a Fed enforcement action aimed at
stopping the holding company from taking steps that are
"unsafe or unsound" for its bank subsidiaries.
   The district court ordered the Fed to halt its enforcement
effort that charged MCorp with requiring two of its banks to
make unsecured loans to another MCorp subsidiary. But the
appeals court said the district court didn't have the
authority to halt the Fed action. (Board of Governors of the
Federal Reserve System vs. MCorp; MCorp vs. Board of
Governors)
                                                                                                       

   Lemon Laws
                                                                                                       

   The justices let stand a federal appeals court ruling that
rejected the auto industry's challenge to informal dispute
resolution procedures in New York state's lemon law. Lemon
laws, which exist in most states, protect consumers,
especially car buyers, by setting minimum standards for
sellers' warranties.
   The lawsuit was filed in 1986 by the Motor Vehicle
Manufacturers Association of the U.S., the trade group for
the domestic industry, and the Association of International
Automobile Manufacturers, an industry group for foreign
manufacturers and importers.
   The manufacturers argued that 1986 amendments to New
York's lemon law were pre-empted by a 1975 federal law that
sets minimum standards for warranties, including automobile
warranties.
   The federal law encourages the use of informal means,
short of lawsuits, to settle warranty disputes. The law
doesn't require sellers to offer informal dispute resolution,
but it ordered the Federal Trade Commission to issue minimum
standards for sellers that offer dispute resolution. New
York's law goes further; it requires any seller that offers
dispute resolution to give the buyer a chance for a hearing,
to keep additional records, and to rely on personnel trained
in arbitration.
   The auto industry argued that the federal law left no room
for more stringent state regulation. But a federal appeals
court in New York ruled in March 1990 that Congress intended
to set only minimum standards for resolving warranty disputes
and didn't intend to bar the states from giving consumers
additional protection. Yesterday, the Supreme Court refused
to hear an industry appeal, although two justices, Byron
White and Harry Blackmun, voted to hear the case. (Motor
Vehicle Manufacturers Association vs. Abrams)
   (See related story: "High Court Upholds Award Of $1.1
Million Against Pacific Mutual Insurance" -- WSJ March 5,
1991)
</TEXT>
</DOC>

