<HL> Law: 'Lemon Law' on Cars Survives a Challenge In Connecticut Court </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> F C </CO>
<IN> AUT </IN>
<DATELINE> HARTFORD  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Connecticut's new car "lemon law," the first ever adopted and a model for other states, has survived an important court test. 

   But the fight over the constitutionality of the law, designed to protect new car buyers, is far from over. 
The Motor Vehicle Manufacturing Association, Ford Motor Co., Chrysler Corp., and 20 other opponents could still appeal yesterday's ruling by a Hartford Superior Court judge to the state's Supreme Court. 

   Connecticut's "lemon law," enacted in 1982, gives a new car buyer the right to a refund under certain conditions, for instance if the same defect has to be repaired more than four times. 
The statute also established arbitration panels to decide disputes between car owners and manufacturers. 

   The manufacturers' group challenged the law as unconstitutional, arguing among other things that the arbitration system deprived them of their rights to jury trial. 
But Superior Court judge Mary Hennessey ruled the law passed constitutional muster. 

   The lemon-law's author, State Rep. John Woodcock, called the decision "very significant" because it could encourage other states to go ahead with similar legislation. 
Mr. Woodcock, an attorney, said he expects an appeal, but he added: "I'm hoping the auto industry will realize the best way to resolve the matter is to work with the states to put together sound model legislation." 

   The attorney for the industry group couldn't be reached to comment. 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

