<HEAD>Court Says Ford Must Give Back $100 Deductibles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. illegally charged $100
deductibles to perform some automobile repairs it should have done
in New York State for free under the state's lemon law, a mid-level
state appeals court ruled.
   The Appellate Division of the state's Supreme Court decided
Thursday that Ford was ``unjustly enriched'' by charging New York
consumers the deductibles and must make restitution.
   New York State Attorney General Robert Abrams contended in court
that the state's 1983 lemon law, designed to provide New Yorkers
with replacement vehicles or money back if their new cars exhibit
irreparable flaws, did not allow Ford to impose the deductibles.
   According to court papers, Ford paid the cost of all repairs for
its new cars during the first 12 months or 12,000 miles. But under
an extended limited warranty, the automaker charged $100 each time
it made repairs to the power train and other major components of
cars with 12,000 to 18,000 miles or between one and two years old.
   Abrams argued in court that the state's lemon law prohibits
automakers from imposing a deductible for repairs on new cars
during their first 18,000 miles or two years.
   A state Supreme Court justice in Albany, Harold Hughes, ruled in
December 1986 that the lemon law prohibits Ford from imposing the
deductibles, but he did not order the automaker to provide
restitution.
   In the 5-0 ruling by the appellate division Thursday, however,
Presiding Justice A. Franklin Mahoney said he and his colleagues
``choose to exercise our discretion'' by ordering Ford to give the
money back.
   Mahoney rejected arguments by Ford attorneys that New York's
lemon law is unconstitutional and that it violates interstate
commerce laws.
   Mahoney conceded that while Ford may not have detailed records
of all customers it improperly charged for repairs, ``it would not
be impracticable to give purchasers during the relevant time period
a general notice and a time period to come forward.''
   Mahoney sent the matter back to the state Supreme Court level to
devise an ``appropriate restitution procedure'' for Ford to follow.
   He was joined in his decision by state Supreme Court Justices T.
Paul Kane, John Casey, Leonard Weiss and Thomas Mercure.
   Nancy Connell, a spokeswoman for Abrams, said the attorney
general's office has no accurate total of how many New Yorkers were
improperly charged the deductibles. But she said it's believed
refunds could total ``in the millions of dollars.''
   Philip Lacovara, a Washington-based attorney who represented
Ford in the case, did not immediately return a telephone call
seeking comment.
   The ruling could be appealed to the state's highest court, the
Court of Appeals.
</TEXT>
