      For Car Buyers, 1990 Is
   Closer Than They Think
   WANT A CAR of the future? 
A 1990 model car can be yours as early as this January. 

   Typically, next-year models are introduced a few months before the year actually starts. 
But just weeks after 1989 begins, Chrysler Corp. will roll out the Plymouth Laser and bill it as a 1990 model. 
General Motors Corp. will launch its 1990 Chevrolet Lumina sedan in May. 
Nissan Motor Co.'s new 300 ZX sports coupe and its minivan make their debuts next spring as 1990 models. 

   Actually, Chrysler officials say, the company could have introduced the Laser this fall instead of waiting until next year, because production is running ahead of schedule. 
But launching a 1990 model car before 1988 ends would have been absurd. 

   Or worse. 
A federal regulation prevents auto makers from introducing 1990-model vehicles more than 12 months before that year actually begins. 
Auto makers stretch the rule to its limits to attract buyers looking to slow their cars' depreciation. 

   Lemon Law Leaves
   Buyers With Sour Taste
   LEMON LAWS are supposed to protect consumers from lousy cars, but for New York state buyers, protection carries a high price. 

   That's because New York is the only place where both Ford Motor Co. and GM tack a surcharge onto the base price of their vehicles to cope with the cost of complying with the state lemon law. 
Since last year Ford has charged New York car buyers an extra $115. 
GM charges $65. 

   The charges reflect the cost of warranty provisions required by the lemon law, the companies contend. 
The law requires basic warranty coverage for 24 months or 18,000 miles, and prevents manufacturers from charging a $100 deductible for warranty visits during that period. 
Ford's basic coverage ends after 12 months or 12,000 miles. 
GM requires a $100-per-visit deductible after that time, although its basic coverage extends for three years or 50,000 miles. 
"No other state lemon law has extended our basic warranty coverage," Louis R. Ross, a Ford executive vice president, wrote to New York Gov. Mario Cuomo to explain the extra charge. 

   But consumer groups don't buy that explanation. 
The surcharge is "an attack on the lemon law by the manufacturer by making {the law} seem like it's a consumer burden," argues the Center for Auto Safety in Washington, D.C. 

   The war has gone beyond words. 
After Ford itemized the surcharge on each vehicle's window sticker, the New York state Legislature passed a bill prohibiting the company from identifying it as a "charge" due to the lemon law. 
Then two industry trade groups sued the state, attacking the lemon law's constitutionality. 

   Last May, the groups won a partial victory. 
A federal court in New York ruled the state couldn't ban manufacturers from telling consumers the reason for the surcharge. 
But decisions on whether New York can require car makers to extend their basic warranty coverage or whether it can ban deductible payments during the warranty period are pending. 

   Station Wagons Fade
   As Minivans Surge
   AS MORE FAMILIES pile the kids into the minivan, more auto makers drop the family station wagon. 

   Mazda Motor Corp., which just launched its first U.S. minivan, recently discontinued the wagon version of its 323 subcompact car. 
GM's Chevrolet division won't have a station wagon in its new Lumina line of midsize vehicles, which includes a sedan, coupe and an "all-purpose vehicle." 
The APV, which is another name for minivan, makes it debut next fall. 
Chrysler's next generation of family cars, the Dodge Spirit and the Plymouth Acclaim, will come in a sedan version only. 
They replace the Aries compact and Reliant "K cars," which included station-wagon versions. 

   Chrysler doesn't think it's "prudent" to invest much money in new station wagons given the popularity of minivans, says copresident Bennett E. Bidwell. 

   Total minivan sales are expected to surge 25% this year to about 744,000 vehicles, putting them above station-wagon sales for the first time. 
By 1990 Americans are expected to buy more than one million minivans a year. 
Station-wagon sales, in contrast, peaked at 1.3 million in 1973, and will drop below 730,000 this year. 

   Station wagons won't disappear, however. 
Chevrolet will continue to produce the midsize Celebrity wagon after it rolls out the Lumina line. 
And Ford plans to keep its Taurus station wagon. 

   A Hidden Cost
   Of Eased Fuel Rules? 

   THE LOWERED federal fuel economy standard for autos will boost small-car prices, an economist predicts. 

   George Hoffer of Virginia Commonwealth University argues that the recent easing of the gas-mileage standard "puts less pressure" on U.S. car makers to offer incentives to boost their small car sales. 
Indeed, while Ford has offered price discounts on its subcompact Escort every year since it was introduced in 1980, there aren't incentives on the 1989 Escort yet. 
And Chrysler has raised the price on its 1989 Dodge Omni subcompact a hefty 10%. 

   In the past, auto makers discounted small cars to increase their sales and thus offset the low gas mileage of their more-profitable large cars. 
Federal regulations set a minimum miles-per-gallon average for an auto maker's entire fleet, so the companies had to sell lots of small cars in order to sell the big ones. 
But now they can sell fewer small cars, because the Department of Transportation eased the corporate average fuel-economy standard for 1989 model cars to 26.5 miles per gallon from 27.5 mpg. 

