<HEAD>State Announces $100 Million Automaker Refund</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Attorney General Robert Abrams on Monday
announced a settlement with 12 car manufacturers that will provide
up to $100 million in refunds to consumers.
   The settlement was reached under the state's ``lemon law'' and
could set a precedent for other states, officials said. Abrams said
he believes it to be the largest refund by automakers in the
nation's history.
   The settlement will provide refunds for all New York residents
who bought or leased new cars after Aug. 2, 1986, and have been
forced to pay for repairs that should have been covered by
warranty.
   The repairs must have been made after the manufacturer's basic
warranty expired (normally during the first 12 months or 12,000
miles, whichever comes first), but before the first 24 months or
18,000 miles, or whichever comes first.
   The state's lemon law requires manufacturers and their dealers
to make repairs under their warranty, at no cost to the customer,
for a period of two years or 18,000 miles, whichever comes first.
   The carmakers who entered into the agreement are Chrysler, Ford,
General Motors, Honda, Hyundai, Isuzu, Mazda, Mitsubishi, Nissan,
Subaru, Toyota and Volvo. Each company also paid the state $10,000
in costs, for a total of $120,000. But they did not admit
wrongdoing in signing the settlement.
   Some carmakers, such as Mercedes-Benz, were not included in the
settlement because their warranty programs are broader than the
state's lemon law, Abrams said.
   Abrams said the settlement was reached after a ``long-fought
effort'' of four years to get the auto manufacturers to agree on
the terms.
   Within the next month, the automakers will place advertisements
in major New York newspapers detailing the refund plan. The ads
will run for six weeks and consumers have 4{ months to respond.
   ``What happens in New York becomes very important to the rest of
the nation and we may see other states taking a look at this,''
Abrams said.
   Since the state's lemon law was expanded in 1986, a record $60
million has been recovered on behalf of consumers, Abrams said.
</TEXT>
