<HEAD>Chrysler To Repurchase Used ``Lemons''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Motors Corp. repurchased nearly 400
defective cars under the state's ``lemon law'' and then allowed
dealers to resell them without warning buyers of their past
problems, according to state Attorney General Robert Abrams.
   The company agreed to make up to $2 million in refunds in a
settlement with the state, Abrams said Thursday. He called the case
``one of the more flagrant violations of the law I've ever seen.''
   Chrysler and American Motors, a Chrysler subsidiary, repurchased
the cars from consumers who won arbitration cases against the
companies under the ``lemon law,'' Abrams said.
   That law defines a car as defective if a problem persists after
four repair attempts or if a car spends a total of 30 days in a
dealer's garage within 18 months of purchase.
   Abrams said the company turned around and resold the cars
without notifying the new buyers of their histories. He also said
Chrysler failed to notify the state Department of Motor Vehicles
that it had repurchased the ``lemons,'' as required by law. That
would have allowed the agency to issue new titles for the cars that
would have alerted used-car buyers of the problems.
   ``Consumers who buy cars are entitled to know of the car's lemon
history,'' said Abrams. ``Chrysler failed to provide this essential
information, which would have allowed consumers to make an
intelligent choice.''
   Chrysler, which admitted no wrongdoing in settling the case,
agreed to pay the state $100,000 in legal costs.
   Under the settlement, Chrysler will offer 205 consumers who
purchased defective cars since last September the option of
returning the cars for a full refund or accepting a $1,000 cash
payment and a 12-month, 12,000-mile service contract.
   Customers who take the service contract option will be entitled
to free repair of any exisiting conditions and reimbursement for
previously documented repairs.
   An additional 185 consumers who purchased lemons between Aug. 2,
1986, and Aug. 31, 1987, will receive $750 cash awards plus the
service contract, free repairs and reimbursement for previous
repairs.
   Chrysler will mail notices to car owners by Oct. 8 and owners
will have 30 days to exercise their option.
