<HL> Connecticut Files Complaint on GM Under 'Lemon' Law </HL>
<AUTHOR> Melinda Grenier Guiles (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> GM </CO>
<IN> AUT </IN>
<TEXT>
   The Connecticut Department of Motor Vehicles has filed a complaint against General Motors Corp., alleging that the No. 1 auto maker violated a reporting requirement in the state's so-called "lemon" law. 

   Under an amendment to the law adopted in July 1987, auto makers are supposed to notify the department of any vehicle that they repurchase because of a defect or problem that isn't repaired to the owner's satisfaction. 
Companies and dealers can resell these vehicles only if the problem is disclosed to potential buyers or repaired and approved by the department. 

   A department spokesman said the agency hasn't been notified of any repurchases since the statute was amended, despite the fact that "roughly 400" vehicles have been declared lemons under the state's arbitration program in the past 11 months. 

   He said the department filed its complaint against GM because it discovered during an investigation that GM had sold unreported cars to dealers at a company-sponsored auction. 
He said the investigation was prompted by recent reports in the Hartford Courant that some consumers had unknowingly purchased vehicles that had been declared lemons. 

   State officials said they are looking into the allegations raised by the Courant. 
They also said they are continuing the investigation to determine whether other manufacturers or dealers have violated the requirement that repurchased vehicles be reported to the motor vehicle department. 

   GM hasn't yet received "a formal citation" or "any informal inquiry" about the matter, said a spokesman in Detroit. 
But GM considers the problem "basically a misunderstanding regarding administrative procedures" and hopes to resolve it before a July 21 administrative hearing. 
The fact that no company has provided information about repurchased cars "may be because the state has not yet provided direction about how that portion of the law should be carried out," he said. 

   He added that GM's practice in Connecticut has been to repair repurchased vehicles and then resell them to dealers at auction, clearly identifying the vehicles as repurchased by special "literature" and window stickers. 
"We would hope that dealers would disclose that information" to potential customers, he said. 

</TEXT>
