<TEXT>
      A Cold Shoulder
   To Longer-Term Loans
   CONSUMERS ARE shunning extended-term car loans despite the lower monthly payments. 

   Volvo Cars of North America says only about 100 buyers have signed up for the 10-year auto loans it introduced with much fanfare in February. 
"We've only done one here," says Kelly Coghill, assistant sales manager at Don Beyer Volvo in Falls Church, Va. 

   One hurdle is the required 20% to 25% down payment on the loans. 
Interest rates also can be as much as three percentage points higher on the 10-year loans than on traditional five-year loans. 

   The monthly payment on a $22,755 Volvo 740 GLE, financed for 10 years at 11.25%, would be roughly $250 a month, after a 21% down payment. 
Buyers making the same down payment with a five-year loan at 9.5% would pay about $377 a month. 
The catch: Total interest payments on the 10-year deal are significantly higher -- $12,036 compared with $4,673. 

   Chrysler Corp., the only other major auto maker to offer extended contracts on a regular basis, also hasn't found many takers for the six-year loans on its minivans; only about 7% of all minivan buyers in the year ended March 31 opted for these loans. 

   Volvo and Chrysler say, however, that the programs are attracting customers who ultimately choose another form of financing. 
"Our motivation is not to sell 10-year contracts," says a Volvo spokesman. 
"Our motivation is to sell cars, and at least it is an attention-getter." 

   Used-Car Buyers Get
   A Little More Protection
   LEMON LAWS are spreading slowly to used cars. 
About 45 states have such regulations covering new-vehicle sales. 
Now, Massachusetts and Minnesota soon will join the District of Columbia, Rhode Island, New York and Connecticut in adopting laws that require warranties for used cars and trucks. 

   The Massachusetts law, which takes effect July 1, covers vehicles that cost $700 or more and have less than 125,000 miles at the time of sale. 
The Minnesota law applies, starting Aug. 1, to vehicles that are less than eight years old, have been driven less than 75,000 miles and have sticker prices of at least $3,000. 

   Most laws guarantee buyers a warranty of at least 30 days on specified parts. 
All also outline the criteria under which a vehicle would be considered a "lemon "usually a problem that isn't repaired after a certain number of days or trips to the dealer. 

   Many car dealers oppose the laws. 
Some complain the laws unfairly exclude sales by individuals. 
Others argue that the laws will force up the prices of used cars. 
And in some cases, state officials fight the laws because they're afraid enforcement will require too much work. 

   Regulators also fear loopholes. 
The $700 cutoff in Massachusetts may lead to "a lot of cars sold for $699," says attorney Paul Gromer of the state consumer affairs office. 

   Boost for Critics
   Of 'Option Packages'
   CAR BUYERS upset about the proliferation of costly car and truck "option packages" are getting a big and vocal ally -- the National Association of Fleet Administrators. 

   The group's members buy about a million vehicles a year. 
And some don't like being required to take, say, tinted glass when they buy air conditioning, or a tilt steering wheel with an automatic transmission. 
Such "packaging" of options has greatly increased because it simplifies the production process -- and thus, say auto makers, improves vehicle quality while cutting costs. 

   But the fleet association, like many individual buyers, complains that the price "discounts" attached to the packages often don't offset the extra cost of unwanted features. 
And often "the packages are very difficult to interpret," says association President Frank W. Kraus, automotive fleet manager for the Anglo-Dutch Unilever Group's Lever Brothers Co. unit. 
"A car may have package A, B and C . . . but A is part of B and B is part of C." 

   The association has discussed the problem with the Big Three, asking the companies to "rethink how they're doing this," Mr. Kraus says. 
One "solution" could be yet more packages -- designed especially for fleet needs. 

   The High Price
   Of Indy 500 Fame
   AUTO MAKERS love to brag that their cars have been picked to pace the Indianapolis 500 race over the Memorial Day weekend. 

   "It's no wonder the all-new Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme was chosen to be the Pace Car for the 1988 Indianapolis 500," boasts a recent Olds ad. 

   But the "honor" isn't cheap. 
In fact, it's so expensive that some companies have been known to decline the opportunity because they didn't feel it worth the price. 

   Olds, for instance, must provide the two specially engineered cars that actually start the race, as well as the clones used in parades and the dozens of courtesy vehicles for celebrities and race officials. 

   In all, about 120 cars. 
And then there's the advertising space the pace-car company must buy in the race program and around the track. 

   "You have to look at it as a promotion," says B.F. "Moon" Mullins, sales and marketing spokesman for Chrysler, whose LeBaron convertible was the 1987 pace car. 

   Indianapolis Motor Speedway, which sponsors the race, declines to comment on its selection criteria. 
And for its part, General Motors Corp.'s Oldsmobile division says its pace-car status is an honor. 
"It's not something that's doled out rather capriciously," says Olds spokesman Mark Rollinson. 
He adds that Olds is willing to pay the cost -- which it won't specify -- for the exposure. 
The May 29 event is expected to attract more than 300,000 fans and will be televised to some 40 million people. 

</TEXT>
