<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. will give New York consumers as much as $2 million in compensation, state officials said, to settle claims that the car maker sold cars it had earlier repurchased under the state's "lemon law" without proper disclosure. 

   The announcement comes just over a year after Chrysler was indicted for selling as new more than 60,000 cars and trucks that had been tested with the odometers disconnected. 
The auto maker eventually agreed to pay $16 million to owners across the country in that case. 

   New York's so-called lemon law requires auto makers to repurchase vehicles if they have been in the repair shop for at least 30 days in the first 18 months of ownership, or if a problem persists after four attempts to fix it. 
The companies often repair the cars and re-sell them. 
But the law requires the companies to tell potential buyers of the earlier problems. 

   An investigation by the New York state attorney general's office concluded that in about 400 cases Chrysler re-sold the vehicles, but didn't disclose their history. 
Under the settlement, Chrysler will give 205 consumers who purchased their vehicles after September 1987 the option of returning the cars for a full refund or accepting a $1,000 cash payment and a 12-month, 12,000 mile service contract. 
Chrysler also will refund past repair bills of customers who select the service contract. 

   Some 187 customers who purchased their vehicles between Aug. 2, 1986, and Aug. 31, 1987, will receive $750 and the same extended service agreement from Chrysler. 
The auto maker also will refund the consumers' previous repair bills. 

   A Chrysler spokesman said the incidents resulted from "completely inadvertant human error," and added that the settlement the company agreed to, "went well beyond the letter of the law." 
By the agreement Chrysler admitted no wrongdoing, but the company has paid New York state $100,000 to cover legal costs. 
The state said the settlement could total $2 million, but Chrysler estimated the total payout at $1.1 million. 

   State officials said they didn't have any consumer complaints, but wanted to investigate what happened to cars repurchased under the lemon law. 
They added that other auto makers also had similar violations, but Chrysler was singled out because it had the most. 
The officials declined to say whether they will announce similar agreements with other auto companies. 

   The Chrysler spokesman said that the company sells 200,000 cars a year in New York and that fewer than 0.1% are considered defective. 

</TEXT>
