<HL> Winnebago's Breakdown-Prone Diesels Assailed by Owners and Consumer Groups </HL>
<AUTHOR> Robert L. Rose (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> WGO </CO>
<IN> AUT </IN>
<TEXT>
   In 1983, Winnebago Industries Inc. introduced its new line of sleek, diesel-powered motor homes, promising a "new era" for recreational vehicles. 

   It was an era that many recreational-vehicle owners came to regret. 
The vehicles turned out to be trouble-plagued machines that can go through diesel engines and transmissions as fast as some cars go through mufflers or cheap tires. 

   The vehicles' names aren't exactly household words: the Winnebago LeSharo, the Itasca Phasar, and a van version called the Centauri. 

   But the Center for Auto Safety says the Winnebago diesels may have the highest percentage of defects of any vehicle since 1969, when the nonprofit consumer group was formed. 
The center estimates that of the 7,800 Winnebago diesels sold before the line was dropped in 1986, one in two is a "mechanical lemon." 
Clarence M. Ditlow III, executive director, says the ratio of problem vehicles rivals only that of the diesel cars made by General Motors Corp. in the late 1970s and early 1980s. 

   The Winnebago diesel line is "one of the worst, if not the worst," of all vehicles, Mr. Ditlow says. 
The center is demanding that Winnebago set up a $100 million fund to compensate diesel owners. 

   Automobile Warranty Corp. says the vehicles are such lemons that it stopped selling service contracts for them in late 1986. 
The Wheat Ridge, Colo., company says it was having to pay claims on at least 80% of all the policies it sold for the vehicles. 
Paul Redd, sales administrator and vice president, says those claims distorted its overall financial picture. 

   Even Winnebago diesels with impeccable maintenance records are plagued by the problems, says Brian Hochhalter, an Automobile Warranty claims adjuster. 
"It's not customer abuse or negligence," he says. 

   Larry Ritze, claims manager for General Mechanical Service Corp. in Mesa, Ariz., says his company also is considering halting the sale of warranty coverage on the diesels, "basically because the losses are so high on them." 

   Owners are so mad that they've talked about forming a caravan to Winnebago headquarters in Forest City, Iowa, to stage a mass protest. 
That could be difficult, though. 
Gene Buckley of Wilmington, Del., for one, says he doubts his LeSharo would make it past Pennsylvania. 

   A typical owner experience: Howard I. Peach says his 1985 Phasar broke down on the way to his mother's funeral, leaving a puff of black smoke and a panel full of red warning lights. 
The tab for a rebuilt diesel engine and turbocharger: $4,300. 
The odometer read 27,000 miles. 

   Similar stories are told by other owners, who spent $20,000 to $30,000 for the vehicles. 
"This dream has become a nightmare for anyone who has owned these things," says former diesel LeSharo owner Richard J. Pelletier, Wilbraham, Mass. 

   The problems aren't limited to the engine and transmission. 
Owners also have complained about turbochargers, bearings, brakes and speedometers, among other things. 
But the main problem appears to center around the Renault-built power train Winnebago selected to use in the LeSharo, Phasar and Centauri. 
Critics say it simply isn't powerful enough to handle the diesel vehicles' three-ton load. 

   The complaints come at a bad time for Winnebago. 
Production problems on the company's assembly lines over the summer led to lost sales, the dismissal of the chief executive officer, and a dismal fiscal fourth quarter, which ended Aug. 27. 

   Frank Rotta, a Winnebago spokesman and member of its management committee, acknowledges the company had problems with the diesel engines purchased from Renault, but he declines to elaborate. 
He does say, however: "We've taken our warranty obligations very seriously here and feel we've fulfilled all terms of requirements under the warranty." 
The warranty covers 12 months or 12,000 miles, whichever comes first. 

   Mr. Rotta won't comment further, citing "some litigation" over the matter with owners. 
He says Winnebago stopped selling the diesel models after 1986 because of low demand and instead began offering only gasoline versions of the three vehicles. 
Some former Winnebago officials, however, say problems with the diesel models led to the switch to gasoline power. 

   A Renault spokesman says the French auto maker is "just a supplier" to Winnebago, and that the motor-home maker "is in charge of its own product, including the engine." 
He says Renault hasn't had problems with the engine in Europe. 

   Unsatisfied with the response from Winnebago, angry owners have formed an informal network to take on the company. 
They leave notes on LeSharo windshields and compile lists of unhappy owners. 
And they hire lawyers. 
Fred Curran, a 67-year-old retiree from Rochester, N.Y., even formed a club of disgruntled owners, which has hired a lawyer to sue the company. 

   The diesel-powered RVs were supposed to cause a different kind of revolution. 
Still suffering from an earnings slump brought on by the gasoline shortage in the late 1970s, Winnebago designed a whole new vehicle, moving away from the traditional heavy coach built on the back of a truck body. 
It would be fuel-efficient and sell for less than $23,000. 
It would have front-wheel drive and an aerodynamic design. 

   The result, introduced in 1983, was a road-hugging, 22 miles-per-gallon marvel that helped Winnebago achieve record sales and near-record earnings that year. 
Though half the weight of a conventional motor home, the LeSharo and Phasar boasted all the conveniences: range, refrigerator, hot-water heater and a bathroom. 
The company's 1983 annual report featured a LeSharo on its cover. 
The new line helped Winnebago boost its market share by 19% in 1984. 

   Mr. Pelletier bought his $22,000 LeSharo the very next year, banking on the reputation that had made Winnebago synonymous with motor home. 
But after 36,000 miles, he says he had replaced the engine, turbocharger and transmission. 
He says he spent $14,000 on repairs before finally selling it to a dealer for $7,000. 

   The Sagamore resort on Lake George, N.Y., bought the van version in 1985. 
Within two years, it had gone through two engines, one turbocharger, two trans-axles, one transmission and three clutches. 
Total cost of those and other repairs: $18,000. 
The hotel's owner says his five Winnebagos -- four of which were diesels -- racked up a total of $50,000 in repair costs. 
The last of the Winnebagos broke down in May. 
"I might drive it into the woods and use it for storage," says Mark Graves, the hotel's director of grounds. 

   "I think the engine is way too small for the size of the vehicle," says Mr. Graves, who is responsible for maintaining the Sagamore's fleet of 35 vehicles. 
"It couldn't take the stress." 

   Some retirees sank much of their savings into the units. 
Mr. Curran says he cashed in a retirement plan to pay for the new engine for his motor home. 
In a letter to Winnebago founder and Chairman John K. Hanson, Mr. Curran said the engine failed after 25 months and 12,000 miles, even though he says he changed oil and filters every 2,000 miles, more often than the manufacturer recommended. 

   Winnebago's reply to Mr. Curran was similar to its response to other owner complaints: "We sincerely regret any inconvenience or expense you have recently encountered," the company said in a letter, but the 12-month, 12,000-mile factory warranty has run out. 

</TEXT>
