<HEAD>Supreme Court Lets Suit Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. must continue to defend a
nationwide suit by some owners seeking damages for defects in
diesel engines after their warranties expired, the U.S. Supreme
Court decided.
   The court refused Monday to review a 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals ruling that consumers can be protected beyond time limits
set by the manufacturer by an ``implied warranty'' that a product
is fit for its ordinary purpose.
   GM lawyers charged that the lower court's August 1989 ruling
``will have intolerable consequences for manufacturers of consumer
products throughout the United States.''
   GM and the Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association said the
ruling could trigger a wave of lawsuits by ``anyone who suffered
repair costs at any time,'' and could extend to all consumer
transactions.
   Lawyers for consumers said GM's arguments were exaggerated.
   The Supreme Court let stand the appeals court's ruling that GM
must defend against a suit by 600,000 owners of 1981-85 cars and
trucks with 5.7-liter diesel engines who made claims for defects
after their warranties expired.
   GM's warranties covered the engines for two years or 24,000
miles for 1981-82 models and three years or 50,000 miles for
1983-85 models.
   Lawyers for the vehicle owners charge GM knew but didn't
disclose that its diesel engines would fail prematurely.
</TEXT>
