<HL> Ford Is Charged With Violating Clean Air Act </HL>
<AUTHOR> Bradley A. Stertz (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> F </CO>
<IN> AUT ENV </IN>
<G> EPA </G>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has accused Ford Motor Co. of violating the federal Clean Air Act by illegally refusing to fully honor emission-system warranties on cars and trucks. 

   The formal allegations, outlined in a letter sent to Ford last week, mark the first time the EPA has formally charged an auto maker with such violations, even though disputes over the warranty coverage have existed for years. 

   Under federal law, the warranties must ensure that a vehicle complies with federal emissions standards for five years and 50,000 miles. 
The law also prohibits vehicle makers from refusing to honor such warranties. 

   In the past, auto makers have often refused to extend the coverage to a defective part, such as a turbocharger or carburetor, if the part causes the emission system to fail. 

   Such refusals technically violated federal laws, but the EPA usually only reminded manufacturers about their responsibilities under the law rather than taking steps to punish them after receiving complaints from vehicle owners. 

   Now the agency said it is stepping up its enforcement after getting an unusually large number of complaints. 
The EPA said it has 23 documented cases in which it alleges Ford improperly withheld required warranty coverage. 

   "Because of the increased concern about emissions control on state and local levels, we determined that we will have a more active role in making sure these manufacturers comply with the Clean Air Act," said Richard G. Kozlowski, a field operations director for the EPA. 
"We're going to be visiting other manufacturers. 
We don't believe Ford is the only manufacturer not acting consistently with the Clean Air Act." 

   A Ford spokesman said the company received the EPA notice Friday, and plans to work closely with the agency to resolve the issue. 
However, the auto maker, in a prepared statement, called the EPA allegations "technical issues" and said it "believes that its longstanding emissions warranty coverage of emission control-related components is fair and reasonable and more than meets the requirements of the Clean Air Act. 

   "We believe, and have suggested to the EPA, that (the) issues are of importance to the industry as a whole and should be addressed through the rule-making process." 

   A Ford spokesman said the EPA action could significantly increase Ford's warranty costs if the company has to cover repairs of faulty parts that cause emissions system failures, as well as the failed emissions systems themselves. 
However, company officials say they haven't yet determined how much their costs could rise. 

   Ford will have 90 days to negotiate a settlement with the EPA or let the allegations go to trial. 
Ford may be liable for a $250,000 civil fine if the matter goes to court and Ford is found guilty of violating the Clean Air Act. 

   The EPA said the penalties against Ford may be mitigated if the auto maker changes the way it honors its emission-system warranty and if it "corrects past improper denials of warranty coverage." 

</TEXT>
