<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   GM to Drop $100 Deductible It Charges
   For Repairs Under New-Car Warranty
   ----
   By Gregory A. Patterson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
06/13/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   F GM
</CO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
</MS>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<RE>
MICHIGAN (MI)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- General Motors Corp. reopened the auto
industry's warranty war, saying it will drop a $100
deductible it has charged for each repair visit under its
basic new-car warranty. But the new policy, which starts with
1992 models, will cover most GM vehicles for fewer miles.
   GM's new warranty plan follows the trend among Japanese
and European auto makers toward offering warranties that are
shorter in duration but cover practically all the car's parts
and promise repairs at no charge. GM found that customers
resented being charged as much as $100 every time they
brought a vehicle in for repairs under GM's two-year-old
"bumper-to-bumper" warranty that covers cars for three years
or 50,000 miles, one company official said. GM's Cadillac
division dropped the $100 deductible in 1990, and "customers
responded very favorably," GM President Lloyd E. Reuss said
in a statement.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The deductible should never have been there," said
Wertheim Schroder analyst John Casesa. "The savings resulting
from the deductible are small compared to the ill will it
generated."
   GM's U.S. rivals, Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Co., which
also have deductibles in most of their warranty coverages,
said they were studying GM's move. Analysts expect Ford to
match GM's move.
   During the 1980s, the Big Three sought to use their
warranty policies to gain a marketing edge. Chrysler was
particularly aggressive, offering six-year and then
seven-year or 70,000-mile coverage for its engines and
transmissions. But those so-called power train warranties
didn't cover common annoyances, such as wind noise or
defective door handles. Now, analysts say, customers are
demanding that manufacturers fix any problem with a new car.
   Under GM's current warranty, the company offered to fix
most defects within three years or 50,000 miles of purchase.
But the $100-deductible provision kicked in after the first
12 months or 12,000 miles.
   GM's new warranty will offer free repairs for three years
or 36,000 miles.
   GM's Cadillac division will keep its four-year,
50,000-mile warranty plan, under which there have been no
deductible charges.
   GM apparently hopes to convince shoppers that its new,
1992 models are of such high quality that it can afford to
fix anything that goes wrong in the first three years for
free. That's the message Toyota Motor Corp. and Honda Motor
Co. have sent by covering practically all parts in their
models for three years or 36,000 miles and charging no
deductibles for covered repairs.
   GM dealers welcomed the change. "It's a better program
when you have something with no deductible rather than
insulting the customer with a $100 fee," said Steven
Hainline, general sales manager at Friendly Chevrolet in
Dallas. "The consumer found the deductible quite petty."
   Ford officials said they may respond to the move once they
see the details. "We will certainly review the program and
take it under consideration," a Ford spokeswoman said. On
most of its cars and all of its pickup trucks, Ford offers a
12-month, 12,000-mile basic warranty with no deductibles. The
engine and transmission are covered differently. On those
components Ford offers a four-year, 50,000-mile warranty that
carries a $50 deductible.
   Chrysler covers most of the parts on its cars for 12
months or 12,000 miles with no deductibles. The engines and
transmissions of Chrysler vehicles are covered for seven
years or 70,000 miles with a $100 deductible that kicks in
after 12 months. Chrysler officials said they aren't likely
to respond immediately to GM's new policy.
   "We don't feel the $100 deductible is that much of an
issue when you're considering the more expensive potential
costs in the engine and drive train," a Chrysler spokesman
said.
</TEXT>
