<HEAD>Court Says Consumer Laws No Protection for Those Who Lease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State and federal consumer protection
laws don't cover leased vehicles, a Florida appeal court ruled.
   A three-judge panel of the 1st District Court of Appeal
concluded in a unanimous opinion Tuesday that Florida's Uniform
Commercial Code and the federal Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act should
cover leased cars, but they don't.
   ``Obviously, in today's market place, a compelling case can be
made for applying the principles of the Magnuson-Moss Act to
transactions of the type before us, but that remains a matter for
legislative decision,'' the judges wrote.
   Both laws permit purchasers to return vehicles and other new
items that have numerous defects not satisfactorily repaired by
dealers and manufacturers.
   The judges said it was the first time a Florida appellate court
had ruled on the issue.
   The opinion upheld a decision by Circuit Judge A.C. Soud Jr.,
who ordered a directed verdict in favor of Frank Griffin AMC Jeep
Inc. of Jacksonville and American Credit Corp. in a suit filed by
Timothy L. Sellers and Kristi H. Sellers over a defective lease
vehicle.
   The dealer had refused to take back the Sellers' new Jeep
Cherokee or refund their down payment and lease payments after the
car allegedly developed numerous problems, including an engine that
exploded, rattles and leaks, seat covers that separated, brakes
that failed and an air conditioning system that didn't cool.
   Soud and the appeal judges found neither state nor federal law
covered the couple because the statutes apply only to sales
transactions.
   The Sellers would have wound up paying about the same as if they
had purchased the vehicle, because they would have had to carry
insurance and have the car serviced and repaired.
   ``The legal incidents of a lease vary significantly from those
of a sale, and the parties' unambiguous expression of intent to
create only a lease cannot be overturned by this court through
legal recharacterization of the transaction,'' the judges wrote.
   ``Transactions like this one obviously should be made subject to
UCC provisions for revocation of the acceptance when a defective
vehicle is delivered pursuant to either a sale or a long term
lease,'' the judges stated. ``Nevertheless we must leave this
solution to the Legislature.''
</TEXT>
