<HEAD>Equipment Makers Say Sharp Reduction of Auto Pollution is Possible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The companies that make motor vehicle
anti-pollution equipment predict they can meet the tough emissions
standards proposed in a clean air bill favored by environmentalists
but denounced as too extreme by the auto industry.
   Strongly disagreeing with auto industry witnesses, the
Manufacturers of Emission Controls Association told a House panel
Tuesday that its companies could produce pollution control
equipment that would meet the proposed standards for 100,000 miles
of driving each vehicle.
   Bruce Bertlesen, executive director of the group, said the
association based its assessment on continuing progress in
developing better anti-pollution equipment, more advanced engine
controls and continued reduction of lead contamination in unleaded
fuel.
   ``The most serious challenge to meeting these more stringent
emission standards is maintaining emission control performance
during the useful life of the vehicle under real world
conditions,'' the association said. ``We believe the engineering
challenges can be resolved.''
   At a hearing of the House Energy and Commerce health
subcommittee, the association strongly endorsed emission testing
programs to ensure that owners keep their vehicles properly tuned.
   Bertlesen testified at the first hearing on legislation by Rep.
Henry A. Waxman, D-Calif., subcommittee chairman, to reduce air
pollution at a time that virtually every U.S. city has failed to
meet federal air quality standards. While reducing pollution from
motor vehicles is a major part of the bill, it also attempts to cut
emissions from industrial sources and consumer products.
   But the debate over auto, truck and bus emissions standards is
likely to determine whether Congress _ as happened last year _ lets
a clean air bill die in a legislative stalemate.
   The Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association of the United
States, representing the ``Big Three'' U.S. automakers, told
Waxman's panel the best way to reduce pollution from motor vehicles
is by waiting for the normal phase-out of older cars still on the
road.
   Thomas H. Hanna, president and chief executive officer of the
association, said less than half the vehicles now in use were built
under the latest emissions standards. He blamed the older vehicles
for nearly 90 percent of the hydrocarbon and carbon monoxide
emissions, and more than 7 percent of the nitrogen oxides _ major
pollutants from motor vehicles.
   He predicted that a further tightening of emission requirements
would have ``a minimal air quality benefit compared to vehicle
fleet turnover.''
   Gregory Dana, vice president of the Automobile Importers of
America Inc., representing major manufacturers of foreign cars,
called Waxman's bill ``extreme and unreasonable'' and said the
legislation presents a challenge that is ``simply unattainable.''
   Waxman's bill would toughen tailpipe emission standards for
hydrocarbons and nitrogen oxides; set new requirements to reduce
hydrocarbon pollution from the evaporation of gasoline at the pump
and on the road; and require that emission controls last the full
useful life of an automobile.
   The tailpipe standards would kick in for passenger cars
beginning in the 1992 model year and become even tougher in the
2000 model year.
   An alternative bill, sponsored by nine House members as a
compromise between the auto industry and the environmentalists,
would toughen current standards but not nearly as much as the
Waxman bill. The nine lawmakers would use the best available
technology in requiring new emissions requirements starting in
1993, while the Waxman measure aims to force automakers to develop
new anti-pollution technology.
   Backing Waxman's position were environmental groups including
the Sierra Club and the Natural Resources Defense Council, and
public officials representing state and county governments,
including Vermont Gov. Madeleine M. Kunin representing the National
Governors' Association.
   ``Mobile sources account for half, or more, of the air
pollutants that threaten public health in our cities, and we simply
must demand more of the motor vehicle manufacturers,'' she said.
``We need automobiles that drive us where we want to go, without
driving us to environmental destruction,'' she said.
</TEXT>
