<HEAD>Massachusetts Governor Signs Stringent Clean-Air Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVE EPSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis signed a clean air bill
Thursday that goes beyond new federal requirements for auto
emissions in limiting pollutants blamed for acid rain and the
greenhouse effect.
   The measure is based on California's tough new standards.
Supporters said Massachusetts is the first state in the nation to
go along with California's tighter controls.
   State Rep. David Cohen, who sponsored the bill, said last week's
passage of the standards in Massachusetts may encourage other
states to follow.
   ``There are many, many states that are looking at doing what we
did, but they were afraid,'' Cohen said. ``Massachusetts was a
trailblazer in this action.''
   ``We hope to create a domino effect,'' said Jenny Carter of the
Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group.
   Massachusetts air quality failed to meet federal health
standards on at least 40 days during the past three summers. ``This
law will help reverse that trend,'' Carter said.
   New York also is considering the California standards, said
Benjamin Marvin of the New York State Department of Environmental
Conservation.
   The Massachusetts bill says the new standards will be phased in
beginning in 1993, but in reality state officials reached a verbal
agreement with automobile manufacturers to start the program with
the 1995 model year.
   Carter said she expects most manufacturers will adapt to the new
law by refining catalytic converters.
   She estimated that the measure would cost consumers an extra
$170 when they buy a new car, but tighter warranty standards
included in the new law would help defray that one-time cost.
   The plan calls on car makers to cut smog-causing hydrocarbon and
nitrogen oxide emissions by 50 percent to 75 percent beyond what is
required under the new federal Clean Air Act, averaged over their
entire fleet.
   Dukakis said the federal government must do more to fight
pollution and to save energy so that the United States becomes less
dependent on foreign energy supplies.
   ``There's one other way to clean the air and that's to make
automobiles more efficient,'' Dukakis said.
   An operator at General Motors Corp. in Detroit said company
officials would not be available to comment because of the
holidays, and a recorded message at Ford Motor Co. said offices
there are closed until Jan. 2.
   Dukakis also signed two other environmental bills, one to
protect endangered species and the second to make local
conservation commission members front-line agents in monitoring
wetlands protection laws.
   The endangered species bill protects the habitat of threatened
species from alteration. It also establishes a process for listing
species as endangered, threatened or of special concern and
prohibits the taking or selling of species that make the list.
   The wetlands conservation measure gives local conservation
commissioners the power to protect wetlands. In 1988, the state's
Supreme Judicial Court ruled that the conservation commission
lacked authority to enforce the wetlands protection act.
</TEXT>
