<HL> Court Reinstates Ruling Requiring EPA To Adjust Auto Fuel-Economy Estimates </HL>
<AUTHOR> Stephen Wermiel (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> GM F </CO>
<IN> AUT </IN>
<G> EPA JUS </G>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A divided federal appeals court reinstated an earlier ruling that requires the Environmental Protection Agency to adjust its fuel-economy estimates for vehicles. 

   The action may lead to increased federal penalties against General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. for falling short of federal gas-mileage standards. 
When the original decision was issued by a three-judge panel here in December 1986, the Center for Auto Safety, a consumer watchdog group, estimated that it could cost General Motors $250 million and Ford $50 million in penalties. 

   Federal law requires that auto manufacturers meet vehicle gas-mileage standards enforced by the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. 
Vehicles' gas mileage is tested according to EPA procedures. 
In June 1985, the EPA aided manufacturers by retroactively boosting its gas-mileage estimates for cars made since 1980 to allow for changes in testing procedures that depressed fuel-mileage calculations. 

   But in a suit by the Center for Auto Safety, the appeals court ruled in December 1986 that the EPA also had to take into account changes in testing procedures that increased gas-mileage estimates, not just those that depressed the calculations. 

   The original ruling was wiped off the books in February 1987, when the full 11-member appeals court voted to reconsider the case. 
At issue was whether the Center for Auto Safety should have been allowed to challenge the EPA standards in the first place. 

   Yesterday, the full court, with only 10 members voting on the case since Judge Robert Bork resigned in February, split 5-5 over whether the watchdog group's stake in the dispute was sufficient to give it standing to file the suit. 
Unable to resolve the standing question despite four separate opinions totaling 94 pages, the appeals court assumed that the consumer group was a proper party in the case. 
So, it reinstated the 1986 decision, which was written by Chief Judge Patricia Wald. 

   As has been the case on some other recent occasions, the appeals court was split along ideological lines, with five judges appointed by Democratic presidents voting to approve the watchdog group's standing and five appointed by President Reagan opposed. 

   Auto makers have long been disturbed by the fuel-economy standards. 
Yesterday, a GM spokesman said, "The (court) decision is symptomatic of the burdensome problems" created by the standards. 

   Consumer groups counter that Congress intended to force auto makers to manufacture more-fuel-efficient cars and that the standards are necessary for that goal. 

   Enforcement of the fuel-efficiency standards operates on a complex system in which auto makers are penalized for falling short of standards and gain credits for exceeding them. 
The new rule that the EPA will have to issue likely will wipe out some credits that GM and Ford were to receive based on adjustments in the testing for model years 1980 through 1984. 

   The two companies may be able to offset some of the loss, though, with credits they have gained for exceeding standards for more-recent model years. 
The more-recent standards have been lowered by federal officials. 

   ---
   John Bussey in Detroit contributed to this article. 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

