      For Dealers, Extras
   Become More Crucial
   SOMETHING TO keep in mind next time you walk into a car dealership: Increasingly, the salesman is counting on you to shell out several thousand dollars after you pay for the car. 

   For years, dealerships have sold services in addition to the car itself. 
Extended warranties. 
Rustproofing. 
Loans. 
Insurance on loans if you can't pay. 

   But the importance of these "financing and insurance" products to dealers is escalating. 
"More money can be made here than on the actual sale of a new vehicle," says a trade publication. 
The National Automobile Dealers Association says dealers on average received 13.4% of car-sale gross profits from financing and insurance products during the first half of this year, up from about 8% in 1983. 

   "Competition is getting ever more keen in the automobile business, and profit margins continue to narrow," says James J. Madden Jr., executive vice president for operations and marketing of Chrysler Corp.'s credit arm. 
"Any additional source of income becomes more important." 

   Auto makers say that demand is strong for the extras because people are keeping cars longer, increasing concerns about their ability to pay for the car over time, and about maintenance. 

   But consumer groups complain that naive car buyers are being pressured into purchasing additional services. 
"A lot of people do their homework in buying their car, shopping around," says Peter G. Drymalski, an investigative attorney with the the Montgomery County (Md.) 
Office of Consumer Affairs. 
"But they are then totally unprepared when they go in to the F&amp;I department." 

   Some customers also complain that dealers automatically write insurance into financing contracts without saying it's optional. 

   "F&amp;I is bad when it's dealership-income driven," says Louis Carrio, assistant manager of General Motors Acceptance Corp.'s sales department. 
But, he adds, "it's good when it's customer-service driven that also produces income." 

   Is it Safe? Depends
   On Whom You Ask
   WHILE CAR BUYERS are paying more attention to safety, it's difficult to compare just how safe different cars are. 
It isn't that figures aren't available. 
It's just that they contradict each other. 

   The most commonly cited study is the federal government's crash test. 
That supposedly determines the likelihood of surviving a head-on collision, traveling 35 miles per hour into a wall. 

   But compare the results for 1988 models with the Highway Loss Data Institute's index of insurance collision claims on cars. 
Of the twelve 1988 model vehicles rated by both groups, half got contradictory ratings. 

   For example, the Chevrolet Astro Van finished 60% below the acceptable level on the federal government's test, and was one of the worst in its class of vehicle. 
But, according to the Highway Loss Data Institute figures, the Astro Van has the best record of all vehicles tested-70% better than average. 
Meanwhile, the government says the two-door Pontiac LeMans had one of the best scores among subcompacts, about 20% better than the acceptable level. 
The highway institute ranked it near the bottom, 65% worse than average. 

   "We feel we're reporting on what's happening in the real world," says Richard O. Elder, a vice president of the highway institute. 
Defenders of the government numbers say the real-world data doesn't necessarily measure the structural safety of a car -- that certain cars, such as sports cars, tend to attract unsafe drivers and therefore have higher accident rates. 

   At GM, Squeaky Wheels
   Stand to Gain
   GENERAL MOTORS Corp.'s Oldsmobile division started mailing letters in May to 383,000 owners of its 1985 model-year Cutlass Ciera, Ninety-Eight and Delta 88 cars, asking about their experiences. 
If they report significant dissatisfaction, they get some recompense, up to a $1,500 rebate on a new Olds. 

   "We're just trying to retain our owners and possibly reach a few new buyers," says Ivan W. Stebbins, Olds's assistant general sales manager. 

   But, rather than measuring current dissatisfaction, the survey may invite complaints. 
Customers who report no problems get a letter thanking them for their support, while those who scream get money. 
"I'd rather they be talking to us than somebody else," explains Charles Golden, manager for service promotion. 

   Olds expects to get up to 150,000 responses and offer as many as 8,000 rebates. 

   Auto-Repair Hot Line:
   Help or Hindrance? 

   FOR MANY, the only thing worse than having a car break down is taking it to a mechanic. 
Ron Vincent says he's giving wary consumers a weapon: an auto "tech talk" hot line. 

   Mr. Vincent -- a former Ford Motor Co. mechanic, inventor, and self-proclaimed under-hood expert -- set up his service in May in Dearborn, Mich. 
For $19.95, motorists in distress can call him, describe the car's symptoms, then get an instant prognosis on what the car needs and how much it should cost. 

   If the mechanic argues with his prescription, Mr. Vincent or a sidekick will show up to argue with you, armed with information about consumer-protection laws. 
And he says if he's wrong, he will refund your money. 

   For now, Mr. Vincent is focusing on southeast Michigan, but says he's going nationwide on Nov. 1. 

   But some say the hot line is itself a dishonest ploy. 
"How in God's name can someone diagnose something over the phone?" asks Ronald H. Weiner, president of a national automotive-repair trade group. 

