<LEADPARA>  Q  Is there a law requiring every building in California to be accessible to
the physically handicapped? We visit a wonderful restaurant, but the 10 steps
in front have no railings. Anyone with a cane or a slight handicap needs help.
We're not asking for a wheelchair entrance, just a railing to help us to the
entrance.;    -- A.W., Palo Alto  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  GETTING BETTER ACCESS REQUIRES A FEW STEPS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Action Line  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  A  There is a law -- Title 24 of the California Uniform Building Codes -- that
requires commercial buildings built after July 1, 1982, to be equally
accessible to disabled and able-bodied people, says George Overby, a civil
engineer with the Santa Clara County Building Inspector's Office. Buildings
built before Title 24 went into effect do not have to conform to the code
unless any major remodeling that requires a building permit is done. Then the
entrance of the building and access to the remodeled portion must be made
accessible to disabled people. Title 24 requires stairs of conforming
buildings to have railings. To find out whether that restaurant is subject to
Title 24, call the building department of the city the restaurant is in.;
WRITING HONDA'S BIG WHEEL;  Q  Do you know the name and address of the person
in charge of Honda car company in Japan? I would like to write the head person
about my 1985 Honda Civic, which at 5 years old needed several major repairs.
I called Honda's Southern California headquarters to complain and was told my
car was too old for any help or compensation. The person I talked to refused
to give me the name of the head of Honda. He said he would give it to me only
if I bought a new '91 Honda.;    -- Jim Cummins, Pacifica; A  We've got that
information, and we'll let you have it without making you buy a car. The
president of Honda Motor Co. Ltd. is N. Kawamoto, and you can write him in
care of Honda Motor Co. Ltd., No. 1-1, 2-chome, Minami-Aoyama, Minato-ku,
Tokyo 107, Japan. Unfortunately, the person you talked to at Honda was
probably right about your 5-year-old car. Unless a vehicle's in its first year
or has been driven less than 12,000 miles, it's not covered under the state's
Lemon Law, which entitles the owner of a "lemon" to compensation. A new car
may be considered a lemon if it has had to be brought in to the shop four
times to repair a single defect or it spent at least 30 calendar days in the
shop because of repairs on any number of defects.; LANDING AIR-FARE CREDIT; Q 
An unconfirmed and unauthorized plane ticket was charged to my American
Express Card on the same day I went to pick up my tickets for a Christmas
vacation. The unauthorized plane ticket was for $578 from Los Angeles to
London and appeared on my American Express charge card statement. This is
credit-card fraud. Please help to get my charge card properly credited.;    --
R. Chuapoco, Sunnyvale; A  Your American Express account has been credited
with the $578, says Dick Herron, spokesman for American Express. Herron says
TWA had to wait until American Express officially informed the airline of the
problem.  </TEXT>
