      Rustproofing: A Bad,
   But Profitable, Idea? 

   DEALERS CONTINUE to hard-sell rustproofing for cars even though many manufacturers say it's useless and perhaps even harmful. 

   The motivation for dealers is simple: big profits. 
By spraying cars with $50 worth of materials, they can slap an additional $200 or more on the price of the car. 

   "We heartily encourage buyers to get as much protection as possible for an investment as large as a car," says John Schmitz, general manager of Feld Chevrolet in St. Louis. 
"But I'm not going to deny rustproofing is a very good source of income for us." 
Other dealers say much the same. 

   But most Japanese cars now come with body-rust warranties of three to five years. 
In the last year, General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. have raised the warranty to six years or 100,000 miles from only three years. 
And Chrysler's warranty lasts for seven years or 100,000 miles. 
With improved body metals, especially steel that's galvanized on both sides, GM has even stopped offering rustproofing as a factory-approved "part." 

   "We don't want people, frankly, screwing around with the car and gunking things up," says GM President Robert C. Stempel. 
After-market rustproofing requires the drilling of tiny holes into a car's underbody or interior panels, he explains, so "you see wires cut because the guy drilled through something, not realizing what was on the other side." 
That concern has become critical, Mr. Stempel adds, as cars have gotten smaller and auto makers have crammed more sensitive electrical gadgets behind door panels. 

   Dealer Ratings Are
   Needed -- And Unlikely
   FINDING REVIEWS of cars and trucks on the market is simple. 
Finding ratings on dealers that sell the vehicles remains impossible. 

   The only consistent measures of dealership performance are consumer-satisfaction surveys that auto makers take to judge their franchisees' service departments, pricing strategies and sales techniques. 
Some auto executives concede ratings would benefit car shoppers, who now can judge individual dealers only by word of mouth, or by their own past experience. 
But companies aren't about to turn the surveys loose publicly. 

   "That is something we have no intention of doing," says Leonard J. Alaimo, a customer-satisfaction planning manager at Ford. 
"That would kill the spirit of partnership we have to keep with dealers." 
GM's Mr. Stempel says: "We think that's our business. . . . 
If you're a good shopper, you're going to buy at the right dealer." 

   Auto makers say the ratings indirectly benefit their customers, because the ratings are used to advise or punish poor performers and to reward consistently high scorers. 
But only within limits. 
Pulling franchises from consistently weak performers is rare because of sticky legal questions. 
GM's Buick division says it uses the ratings to reward high performers with additional franchise rights. 
But in fact, any dealer with a rating just above average can get an additional franchise. 

   Even using the ratings in this way is going too far, some dealers insist, because dealers get blamed for manufacturers' defects. 
"If you get a car that isn't all it should be," says Ron Tonkin, who owns 15 new-car franchises in the Pacific Northwest, "there's no way the customer will give the dealer good ratings no matter how perfect the service." 

   Shoulder Belts Coming
   For Rear Seats
   AUTO MAKERS, stung by recent court judgments, say that by 1990 almost every car sold in the U.S. will have rear-seat shoulder belts. 
Until then, it's catch as catch can. 

   No law requires rear-seat shoulder belts. 
But auto makers feel the heat: Last December, a federal court jury in Baltimore awarded a family $3.3 million in a suit against Ford. 
A child in the family was partially paralyzed in an accident, and the jury cited, among other things, the lack of a rear shoulder harness. 
Ford isn't planning to appeal. 

   For now, though, consumers have to scramble to get protection. 
Last September, Zillah Davis of Elroy, Wis., died after an auto accident in which she was wearing a rear-seat lap belt. 
Her surviving husband, Louis K. Davis, later wanted to get rear-seat shoulder belts added to his Jeep Cherokee. 
But Mr. Davis's dealer refused to handle installation. 

   Officials at Kayser Jeep/Eagle in Madison, Wis., say only shoulder-belt kits made by outside companies are available for the Cherokee. 
But the dealership's insurer warned that handling such non-factory safety parts could shift future liability from the auto maker to the dealer. 
"There's a real danger for us to handle after-market safety equipment like that," says John Acomb, sales manager of Kayser Jeep/Eagle. 

   Factory-made, rear-seat shoulder belt kits are available for some car and truck models, although many dealers aren't aware they exist. 
Cost: about $60 to $100, depending on the model, plus installation charge. 

   Buyers See the Future
   And Prefer the Past
   TALK ABOUT the car of the future, and most designers envision dazzling dashboard computer displays. 
But the feedback on Buick's Reatta and Riviera, two cars that feature in-dash computers and digital displays, indicates that owners haven't yet caught the fever. 

   On both cars, drivers must press points on a miniature screen to activate such functions as the radio and climate control. 

   But many dealers say buyers wish the recently launched two-seat Reatta came with the option of traditional displays on the dashboard. 
And a San Francisco car leasing agent even warns first-time drivers of the car not to use the computer controls unless the car is stopped to prevent people from being distracted. 

